'''Amto–Musan''' is a [[language family]] of two closely related but not mutually intelligible [[Papuan languages]], [[Amto language|Amto]] and [[Siawi language|Siawi]], of the [[Sandaun Province]] of [[Papua New Guinea]]. Amto–Musan was left unclassified by Ross (2005) (see [[Papuan languages#Ross classification]]) due to lack of data; Wurm (1975) had posited it as an independent family. The family has [[language typology|typological]] similarities with the [[Busa language (Papuan)|Busa]] [[language isolate]], but these do not appear to demonstrate a genetic relationship.

Timothy Usher links the Amto–Musan languages to their neighbors, the [[Arai languages]] and the [[Pyu language (Papua New Guinea)|Pyu language]] in as Arai–Samaia stock.<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/newguineaworld/families/arai-and-samaia-rivers NewGuineaWorld, Arai and Samaia Rivers]</ref>

