{{Infobox language |name=Kenati |region=[[Papua New Guinea]] |speakers=950 |date=1990 |ref = e18 |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea]] |fam2=[[Kainantu–Goroka languages|Kainantu–Goroka]] |fam3=[[Kainantu languages|Kainantu]] |iso3=gat |glotto=kena1250 |glottorefname=Kenati }}
'''Kenati''' is a poorly documented [[Papuan languages|Papuan language]] spoken by only about 950 people (in 1990) in [[Papua New Guinea]]. It is also known as Aziana, Ganati, Kenathi. Specifically, it is spoken in 3 villages located in the [[Eastern Highlands Province]], in the [[Wonenara]] District of Papua New Guinea.<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=gat Kenati at Ethnologue.com]</ref>
Wurm (1960, 1975) placed it in his [[East New Guinea Highlands languages|East New Guinea Highlands]] family as an independent branch. Ross (2005) could not find enough evidence to confirm this, and left it unclassified. However, ''Ethnologue'' (2009) classified it more specifically with the [[Kainantu languages]], another branch of Wurm's East Highlands.
