'''Svetlana Gorshenina''' (also spelt '''Svetlana Goršenina''';<ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb436803639 |title=Goršenina, Svetlana (1969-....) : The private collections of Russian Turkestan in the second half of the 19th and early 20th century [Texte imprimé] / Svetlana Gorshenina |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=catalogue.bnf.fr |language=fr |access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref> born '''Svetlana Michajlovna Gorshenina''' in 1969) is an [[Uzbekistan|Uzbek]] [[historian]], [[art historian]] and specialist on [[Central Asia]], Associate Lecturer at [[Collège de France]] where she held the Chair of History and Cultures of [[History of Central Asia#Prehistory|Pre-Islamic Central Asia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.universiteitleiden.nl/en/news/2018/02/svetlana-gorshenina-will-be-the-central-asia-visiting-scholar-in-february-2018 |title=Svetlana Gorshenina will be the Central Asia Visiting Scholar in February 2018 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=12 January 2018 |website=[[Leiden University|www.universiteitleiden.nl]] |access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=Biographie>{{cite web |url=https://www.svetlana-gorshenina.net/biographie |title=Svetlana GORSHENINA : Biographie |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=www.svetlana-gorshenina.net |language=fr |access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref> Her works appear mostly in French language.
== Career == Under the direction of {{ill|Galina Pugachenkova|fr|Galina Pougatchenkova}} and Valery Germanov, Svetlana Gorshenina has defended her dissertation on the [[epistemology of archaeology]] and [[art history]] of [[Central Asia]].<ref name=DKSAAC>{{cite book |last1=Gorshenina |first1=Svetlana |last2=Rapin |first2=Claude |date=2001 |title=De Kaboul à Samarcande : Les archéologues en Asie centrale |series=[[Collection (publishing)|Collection]] “[[Découvertes Gallimard]]” |volume=411 |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=Éditions Gallimard |page=160 |isbn=978-2-070-76166-1 |quote=About the author}}</ref>
Gorshenina has been a researcher at the Institute of Fine Arts and Institute of History of the [[Academy of Sciences of Uzbekistan]], and of the [[Swiss National Science Foundation]] at [[University of Lausanne]] and [[University of Manchester]]. An associate researcher in the team "Hellenisms of Asia and Oriental Civilisations" of the [[CNRS]] at [[École Normale Supérieure]]. Director of the "Central Asia" programme of the {{lang|fr|Réseau Asie-IMASIE}} (Asia-IMASIE Network), {{lang|fr|[[maître de conférence]]}} at the University of [[Tashkent]].<ref name=Biographie />
She was invited to present her research as a researcher-teacher at the [[School for Advanced Studies in the Social Sciences]] in Paris, and organised a photography exhibition on Western travellers in Central Asia at the [[Musée d'ethnographie de Genève]].<ref name=DKSAAC /> She also organised several [[Academic conference|symposia]], study sessions, [[Round table (discussion)|roundtables]] and [[Panel discussion|panels]] in [[Paris]], [[Lausanne]], [[Geneva]], [[Samarkand]] and [[Manchester]].<ref name=Biographie />
== Selected publications == * ''La route de Samarcande : l'Asie centrale dans l'objectif des voyageurs d'autrefois'', Geneva: Olizane, 2000 * ''Explorateurs en Asie centrale : Voyageurs et aventuriers de Marco Polo à Ella Maillart'', Geneva: Olizane, 2003 * ''The Private Collections of Russian Turkestan in the 2nd Half of the 19th and Early 20th Century'', Berlin: Klaus Schwarz Verlag, 2004 * ''L'invention de l'Asie centrale : Histoire du concept de la Tartarie à l'Eurasie'', coll. "Rayon Histoire" (nº 4). Geneva: Droz, 2014
; Collaborative works * With [[Claude Rapin]], ''De Kaboul à Samarcande : Les archéologues en Asie centrale'', coll. "[[Découvertes Gallimard]]" (nº 411), série Archéologie. Paris: Gallimard, 2001 * With [[Aymon Baud]] and {{ill|Philippe Forêt|fr}}, ''La Haute-Asie telle qu'ils l'ont vue : Explorateurs et scientifiques de 1820 à 1940'', Geneva: Olizane, 2003
